The month of October is designated to highlight domestic violence awareness, but the months that follow can present particularly tough challenges for groups that support survivors.

Historically, domestic violence spikes during the holidays, and shelters often find themselves trying to keep up with increased demands as supplies, volunteers and monetary donations decrease.

Food pantry shelves empty faster, and daily items needed to operate temporary housing or emergency shelter become harder to keep in stock, according to David Moore, executive director of the Angleton-based Women’s Center of Brazoria County.

The following are needs at four women’s shelters and housing facilities in the region that includes Brazoria County, the Bay Area and Pasadena. Click the link in our bio to read more.

The National Domestic Violence Hotline is 800-799-7233.

When U.S. Sen. Ted Cruz’s podcast got picked up by the massive radio network iHeartMedia, the Texas Republican declared it a “big damn deal.” A government watchdog says that big deal is also illegal.⁠
⁠
Senators are prohibited from accepting gifts from lobbyists, which iHeartMedia has. According to the Campaign Legal Center, the company is providing free production and marketing services for Cruz's podcast under an “unprecedented national syndication agreement for a sitting member of Congress.”⁠
⁠
The organization wants the Senate Ethics Committee to investigate the deal.⁠
⁠
A spokesman for Cruz said the senator gets no financial benefit from the deal and compared it to appearing on a cable news show — something virtually every senator does regularly. Click the link in our bio to read more.

A Republican who lost his Houston-area race for a Texas House seat by 15 percentage points is formally contesting the result, arguing Harris County’s Election Day woes mean the outcome should be “declared void and a new election be ordered.”⁠
⁠
Mike May, the GOP nominee who ran against state Rep. Jon Rosenthal in House District 135, filed a petition challenging Rosenthal’s win with the Texas Secretary of State’s Office on Tuesday.⁠
⁠
May contends that the result “is not the true outcome” because some voting locations in Harris County ran out of paper used to print ballots in voting machines.⁠
⁠
Texas Democrats cast the election challenge as a bad-faith political stunt spawned by Donald Trump's baseless accusations that Democrats stole the 2020 election from him through voter fraud and other illicit means.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

As early voting began this year, Democratic Texas House candidate Dr. Suleman Lalani wasn’t facing attacks from his opponent's campaign based on his politics or policy preferences, nor any dug-up dirty laundry or past statements. The vitriol was tied to Lalani's religion.⁠
⁠
Republican Dan Mathews' campaign touted his service as a "Christian minister" in an automated text message that many Fort Bend County voters received, calling for them to stop Lalani from becoming "the First MUSLIM" in Texas state government.⁠
⁠
Lalani took a moment before reacting, consulting with family members and trusted mentors. He recalled former First Lady Michelle Obama’s catchphrase: “When they go low, we go high.”⁠
⁠
Then he told his supporters on Twitter: “Our opponent is hoping Fort Bend voters choose based on fear and hate. Fort Bend is a loving coalition of races, religions, and ethnicities. Together we win over hate.”⁠
⁠
Two weeks later, he and another Pakistani-American Democrat made history. Lalani and Salman Bhojani in Tarrant County’s 92nd District were elected to be the first Muslims and South Asians to serve in the Texas Legislature.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Since the 1980s, an usually high number of young women have mysteriously disappeared in the small cities between Houston and Galveston, many of whom have turned up dead.

One of Netflix's latest true-crime docuseries "Crime Scene: The Texas Killing Fields" tells the story of the unsolved murders of four Texas women that occurred in the 1980s and 1990s in League City.

The series was released on Nov. 29 but the grisly story of the "Texas Killing Fields" has been told in books, a 2011 film, and numerous Houston Chronicle reports on the series of murders dating back to the time they began.

Here are things to know about the Texas Killing Fields. Click the link in our bio to read more.

Reporter St. John Barned-Smith spent months writing about missing persons and unidentified dead cases. Then he began to investigate a case from his own family: His great aunt, Frances St. John Smith, went missing from Smith College almost a century ago.⁠
⁠
On Jan. 13, 1928, Frances arrived at breakfast dressed for class in a simple orange dress, tan shoes and a brown coat lined with skunk fur. It was the beginning of the spring semester at Smith College in western Massachusetts. That unseasonably warm, mid-winter day marked the last time anyone saw her alive.⁠
⁠
Over the course of the next 14 months, there’d be a frantic search to find her, sparked in part by unfounded fears about a serial kidnapper prowling the Smith campus.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

A 7-year-old Texas girl has been found dead, two days after being reported missing, and a FedEx delivery driver has been arrested in her death, authorities said.⁠
⁠
The body of Athena Strand was found Friday, and Tanner Lynn Horner, 31, was arrested on kidnapping and murder charges after confessing to killing the girl and telling authorities where to find her body, according to Wise County Sheriff Lane Akin.⁠
⁠
Horner remained jailed Saturday on $1.5 million bond. Click the link in our bio to read more.

It's not every day that an orangutan lives beyond four decades. The great ape mammals have a life span of roughly 30 to 40 years in the wild, according to National Geographic. But a male orangutan at the Houston Zoo has surpassed that.⁠
⁠
On Thursday, Rudi Valentino, the Houston Zoo's longest living resident, turned 45 years old, the zoo announced. Rudi arrived back in 1978 when he was just two months old, and today he stands at about 5 feet 4 inches with an arm span of about 8 feet 2 inches.⁠
⁠
At his age, Rudi is the oldest living male orangutan in North America, according to the Houston Zoo. But he's not the oldest orangutan in Houston. That crown belongs to Cheyenne, a female orangutan who's been at the Houston Zoo for the past 29 years and recently celebrated her 50th birthday in May.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

NASA's Space Launch System rocket pushed the Orion capsule into space on Nov. 16 from NASA's Kennedy Space Center in Florida.

Houston's Mission Control took over operation right after rocket engines ignited.

Orion was the first spacecraft designed for humans to leave the Earth's orbit since the Apollo 17 mission 50 years ago.

Orion had two close encounters with the moon, flying roughly 80 miles from its surface on Nov. 21 and Dec. 5. It also flew beyond the moon in a large lunar orbit. At one point, Orion was nearly 270,000 miles from Earth — a new record for a spacecraft designed for humans.

The Orion spacecraft returned to Earth on Sunday, Dec. 11. It landed in the Pacific Ocean off the coast of Baja California, Mexico.

University of Texas basketball coach Chris Beard was arrested and charged with assault on a family or household member on Monday.⁠
⁠
Beard, 49, faces a third-degree felony charge of assault against a family member by impeding breath or circulation. A conviction for a third-degree felony carries between two and 10 years in jail.⁠
⁠
Austin police responded to a 911 call from a home with a reported disturbance, which the caller said was no longer ongoing and one of the individuals had left the house. Police located a woman who said she had been assaulted and strangled by Beard, according to the police report.⁠
⁠
Beard’s bond was set at $10,000 during a hearing Monday afternoon, and he left the jailhouse shortly after the hearing without responding to any questions.⁠
⁠

Even though it's December, the recent warmer temperatures have caused mosquitoes to hatch, to the annoyance of many Houstonians who thought they might get a break from the pests as the new year approaches.⁠
⁠
According to the Houston Health Department, mosquitoes lay eggs in ditches, ponds, tanks, and other areas where water collects.⁠
⁠
The eggs can remain in dry conditions for several months and after floods or heavy rains, the eggs hatch in only a few days, producing swarms of hungry mosquitoes. Another wave of mosquitoes occurs typically 10 to 14 days after the rains stop as well.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Mysterious wounds covered a third of Cecilia Tembo’s flesh when she and her mother boarded a Houston-bound plane from Zambia in May 2019.⁠
⁠
No one in their home city of Lusaka had an explanation for the red, painful lesions that suddenly began to spread across the 11-year-old’s body — so severe in spots that her bones and tendons were exposed. Texas Children’s Hospital agreed to take her as a patient.⁠
⁠
Cecilia’s mother said her goodbyes to her husband of 16 years and her 4-year-old son, expecting they’d all be reunited within three months. More than three years later, the family remains separated by 8,000 miles.⁠
⁠
The young girl’s condition proved far more complex than anticipated. It took several days and a citywide conference of Houston doctors to arrive at a diagnosis: a disease so rare it became the subject of an article in the American Academy of Pediatrics.⁠
⁠
Despite intensive treatment, Cecilia, now a 14-year-old freshman at The Woodlands High School, still has not shown enough progress to return to Zambia. She could become critically ill if she leaves, doctors warn.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

⁠
Compared to recent days, Wednesday will be chilly with the arrival of a cold front Tuesday night. High temperatures will be in the mid-60s.⁠
⁠
High temperatures for the rest of the week look to be hovering in the low 60s, but daily low temperatures will dip into the 40s for the remainder of the week, according to meteorologists.⁠

Facing job loss and food insecurity brought on by the COVID-19 pandemic, a group of Congolese refugee women took matters and earth into their own hands.⁠
⁠
Their community garden in Alief broke ground in November of 2020. Shamba Ya Amani, translating to the "Farm of Peace" in Swahili, has continued to grow and thrive alongside the community tending to it since its creation.⁠
⁠
In a city of more than 2 million people, there are almost 200 unique community gardens growing fresh fruits and vegetables for those ready to put their green thumb to the test in the Houston area.⁠
⁠
While community gardens are not a perfect solution to widespread issues such as food insecurity and fresh-produce access, they do offer social and nutritional benefits for those with enough spare time to devote to gardening.⁠
⁠

In addition to the new Olajuwon honor, the NBA also changed the name of five other awards, including renaming the Most Valuable Player award The Michael Jordan Trophy.⁠
⁠
“I am honored to have the opportunity to celebrate the league’s best defensive player each year,” Olajuwon said in a statement released by the team. “Great basketball teams are defined by their ability to defend, with every great team connected by an elite defensive anchor.”⁠

Tucked away in north Midtown, @houstongoodtimes is mostly unassuming. It sits in a could-be-anywhere office building, a could-be-anywhere space stocked with could-be-anywhere furnishings.

But on a $16 flatbread, Chronicle food writer John-Henry Perera found tiny slices of tangy, earthy, cured meat that pointed to somewhere.

Six-thousand miles removed from his native Kosovo, Isa Loshaj and his team continue a more than 100-year culinary tradition. For customers, that sujuk is a window to Isa’s time in Kosovo, the good times and the bad. Read the full story at the link in our bio.

Projects, which would occur during the next 30 years, also will include a backup water system for the medical center, the cluster of marquee hospital systems and research facilities that comprise the world’s largest medical complex.⁠
⁠
To fund the plan, Mayor Sylvester Turner is asking the council to create a Tax Increment Reinvestment Zone, or TIRZ, around the park and medical center.⁠

A winter freeze is headed for Houston this week, and animal welfare organizations are reminding residents to plan ahead for their pets.⁠
⁠
Texas law makes it illegal for pet owners to leave their animals outside in extreme weather conditions, including in temperatures below 32 degrees. The Safe Outdoor Dogs Act, which went into effect this year, offers more protections for animals housed outside.⁠
⁠
The new law was aimed at fixing loopholes in the existing animal cruelty law. It requires animals to have access to adequate shelter during inclement weather, including access to food and water and room to move around comfortably, and bans the use of unsafe restraints and heavy chain tethers.⁠
⁠
Most importantly, the law eliminated a 24-hour waiting period for law enforcement to intervene if they come across an animal in distress.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

As Texas' electric grid prepares to face its biggest cold-weather test since the deadly February 2021 winter storm, ERCOT, the state's grid operator, has advised generators to prepare for a harsh cold blast this week.⁠
⁠
"Our current load forecast for this weekend, which is going to be a very cold event, shows high expected electric demands during the period from Thursday evening through Saturday morning," ERCOT CEO Pablo Vegas said on Tuesday. "We continue to expect adequate supply with reserves for the approaching cold weather conditions. We will continue to monitor and update you as conditions change."⁠
⁠
The cold blast, still more than two days away, could create more demand than officials had anticipated for a winter day. As of Monday evening, ERCOT officials said demand during the upcoming burst of cold was expected to peak at about 9 a.m. Friday at more than 69,312 megawatts — almost 1,900 megawatts more than the grid manager expected for this time of year.⁠
⁠
One megawatt is enough to power about 200 homes. Click the link in our bio to read more.

Santa is going to have to work hard for his cookies this year, as a hard freeze is predicted to settle into the Houston area leading up to Christmas. People are advised to prepare ahead of time for the cold conditions.

Local temperatures could rival the lows of the 2021 winter storm, during which the combination of abnormally icy conditions and high demand for energy across the state led to power outages lasting several days and resulting in the deaths of more than 240 Texans.

Local utilities and the state power grid operator said they're more prepared this winter than they were in 2021.

The sprawling, $1.34 million "Wings Over Water" sculpture outside the city’s convention center was designed to be a draw to a newly renovated downtown plaza, unveiled shortly before Houston welcomed an estimated 150,000 visitors to Super Bowl LI in 2017.

It was billed as the largest kinetic outdoor sculpture in the world, with 70-feet wide wings flapping over streaming jets of water. It also was the most expensive piece of art ever commissioned by the city, paid for with revenues from Houston First Corp., the city's convention arm.

One problem: The wings do not beat at all these days, let alone continuously. And now, city officials have decided, they will stop trying to fix them.

The kolaches here represent the city's top kolache options in his opinion. His flavor profile swings toward doughy bread, fluffy but with some heft; spicy and savory insides that fill up the whole pastry versus just a fraction of it; and fruity jams that aren't overly sweet.

⁠
The order means that universities will no longer be able to use the social media platform to reach fans and prospective students. But a UH System spokesperson said that the order has had minimal effect on university employees.⁠
⁠
Abbott follows several other Republican state leaders in issuing bans of the app on government devices, stemming from fears that the Chinese government is harvesting data from users’ devices.⁠

When Justin Verlander signed with the Mets earlier this month, his new team hadn't done much yet in free agency. ⁠
⁠
Even though it seemed like a safe bet that the Steve Cohen-owned Mets, who had the second-highest payroll in baseball last season, wouldn't be shy about spending money, the former Astros ace still wanted some assurances that he wouldn't be the only addition to the team that won 101 games last season.⁠
⁠
Shortly after signing Verlander to a two-year, $86.6 million contract that ties him with rotation mate Max Scherzer for the highest annual salary in the game's history, the Mets continued their spending spree.⁠
⁠
In the past two weeks, they've added to the rotation by signing José Quintanam Japanese star Kodai Senga and David Robertson, who had a save in the Game 1 of the World Series against Verlander and the Astros. They've also brought back outfielder Brandon Nimmo and added catcher Omar Narváez.⁠
⁠
The Mets' projected payroll should be tops in baseball at around $360 million.⁠
⁠
"I took a leap of faith, and here we are a few weeks later, and I think that leap of faith has paid off," Verlander said. Click the link in our bio to read more.

Rudi Valentino, a male orangutan and one of the Houston Zoo's longtime residents, has passed away at the age of 45.⁠
⁠
Valentino first came to the zoo in 1978 at the age of two months. Since then, he's became the oldest living male orangutan in North America, surpassing the typical life span of his species which is around 30 to 40 years.⁠
⁠
One of his favorite hobbies was to paint, and he became the star artist for the zoo's "Pongos Helping Pongos" art auction and exhibit.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

In an absolutely spectacular turn of events, Carlos Correa — the San Francisco Giants’ anticipated first superstar free-agent signing since Barry Bonds — is instead now a member of the New York Mets.⁠
Correa is the second player the Giants have lost to a New York team this month.⁠
⁠
A source told the San Francisco Chronicle Tuesday that doctors had disagreements over Correa’s physical. That was apparently enough to win the day for the Mets, who swooped in and nabbed Correa with a 12-year, $315 million deal. Correa will join former Astros teammate Justin Verlander, who was introduced Tuesday in New York, with the Mets.⁠
⁠
The Giants had a 13-year, $350 million deal in place with Correa, but it never became official because of the issue with his physical. Correa has a history of back issues, but one source insisted Correa does not have a back problem.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

A day of long lines and furor at Houston’s Hobby Airport after Southwest Airlines canceled hundreds of flights gave way to a somewhat calmer scene Tuesday at the city’s southern airport.

Despite shorter lines inside the building, however, the sense of confusion and frustration remained for hundreds of passengers who unexpectedly found themselves stranded in Houston.

For many, Monday’s uncertainty gave way to a choice between two less-than-ideal options: Should they choose to stay in Houston, possibly for days, and wait for the airline to sort out the problem? Or should they arrange another journey home, whether by ground or by booking a flight with another airline?

Texas Gov. Greg Abbott is firing back at the White House after it harshly criticized him for busing migrants to Washington, D.C., on Christmas Eve in sub-freezing temperatures.⁠
⁠
D.C. officials reported 139 migrants were dropped off near Vice President Kamala Harris’ residence, many of them lacking proper winter clothing.⁠
⁠
As White House officials called the move “cruel, dangerous and shameful,” Abbott Communications Director Renae Eze blamed the White House for not doing more to secure the border.⁠
⁠
Since April, Abbott has bused thousands of migrants to cities with Democratic mayor and governors. On Tuesday, Abbott announced he has now sent 15,900 migrants to D.C., New York City, Chicago and Philadelphia.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

The U.S. Supreme Court on Monday hit pause on the Biden administration's plans to lift a public health order that has been used to expel migrants millions of times, at the urging of Texas and other Republican-led states that argued ending the COVID-19 restrictions would create chaos on the border.⁠
⁠
Chief Justice John Roberts temporarily blocked a lower court ruling that required the Biden administration to let the public health order, known as Title 42, expire on Wednesday.⁠
⁠
The order came after GOP states filed an emergency appeal for the high court to step in, and gives the administration and states more time to make their arguments to the high court.⁠
⁠
The slowdown comes as the White House said Monday that it has sent a record number of agents to the border in preparation for a surge in migration when Title 42 ends.⁠
⁠
Republican Gov. Greg Abbott used a national television appearance over the weekend to warn of “total chaos” if the order is lifted, arguing the nation still doesn’t know the health status of thousands of people trying to cross the border.⁠
⁠

Wednesday dawned in Houston with another 150 Southwest flights canceled out of Hobby Airport, amid the airline’s ongoing struggles to resume normal operations.⁠
⁠
It’s the third day in a row that the airline has canceled more than 150 flights out of the city’s southern airport, and more may be on the horizon.⁠
⁠
The airline Monday announced it would reduce its schedule to one-third of its regular one for several days to help return conditions to normal. It would not be able to rebook flights until Dec. 31 or later.⁠
⁠
Click our link in bio for the latest updates on Southwest flights.

Of the cities with the largest workforces, Houston had the second smallest increase in people working from home — but the change represents thousands of individuals who now work remotely.⁠
⁠
The 2021 five-year estimates from the U.S. Census Bureau show the beginning of an upward trend in the number of people working from home, when compared with data from 2016. The percentage of remote workers increased in every age group, gender, income bracket and industry in Texas.⁠
⁠
Between 2016 and 2021, the city’s total workforce increased by about 18,500 people, and the number of people working from home increased from 37,108 people to 90,607 — a difference of about 53,500 people.⁠
⁠
Read more about the data through our link in bio.

Residents of Houston's Museum District were shocked and horrified to encounter dozens of hateful, antisemitic pamphlets in their neighborhood. ⁠
⁠
The pamphlets, wrapped in sandwich bags and weighed down by pebbles, were a screed of anti-Jewish hate speech and conspiracy theories that have been on the rise in recent years.⁠
⁠
Similar hate pamphlets have surfaced in other Houston-area neighborhoods several times this year.⁠
⁠

One year ago, Krystal Taylor spent the holidays in a bed in the intensive care unit, hoping for the double lung transplant that would save her life.⁠
⁠
The Houston woman never expected her condition to deteriorate so quickly when she went to the Memorial Hermann emergency room with a severe COVID-19 infection in the summer of 2021. She ended up spending nearly seven months in the hospital, including two months in a medically induced coma. By Thanksgiving, doctors determined that she needed a transplant because her lungs were too scarred to function on their own.⁠
⁠
This year, she was finally able to spend the holidays with her family. Read her story through our link in bio.

The Houston area is no different.

Some ordinances — such as the ban on ice cream trucks in Deer Park — seem outdated, while others — including public parks’ varying rules on alcohol consumption — are simply hard to follow.

For nearly 40 years, Demetrius Johnson would lie in bed and imagine what life would be like in the free world. In his mind’s eye, he’d watch himself finding a steady job, getting swept up in romance, marrying the woman of his dreams and raising children.

And then, on Oct. 7, for the first time since he was 17, he actually walked through the prison’s gates.

“Look at me,” he said to the group of friends who had come to pick him up. “You know how it feels to be 55 years old and (have) spent three quarters of your life in the penitentiary?”

Over the following weeks, he would embark on the emotional rollercoaster of trying, finally, to achieve the life he had dreamed of since he was locked up as a high schooler.

Texas is an outlier when it comes to harsh sentences being doled out to juveniles, according to a 2020 report by the Texas Criminal Justice Coalition. While many states set the maximum number of years a juvenile offender can serve before they’re eligible for parole at 20, Texas has set it at 40.

Johnson became eligible for parole after 20 years in the Texas prison system but was not granted parole until he’d been in for 38. And so, like other Texans sentenced to life in their teens, Johnson found himself, in his 50s, trying to navigate a world that had evolved without him.

He hadn’t seen the outside since the '80s — when Prince topped the charts and his mom, grandparents and aunt were still alive. Click the link in our bio to read more.

Whether driven by New Year’s resolutions or a pledge to attempt an alcohol-free 2023, Dry January is upon us.

But the trend for giving up alcohol for the first month of the year doesn’t mean you’re cut out of bar fun entirely. Many Houston restaurants and bars offer mocktails and creative mashups that mimic traditional cocktails without alcohol.

Some are fashioned with zero-proof spirits, others are mergers of fruit juices, syrups and sodas.

If you’re on the bandwagon, here are seven Houston spots offering thirst-quenching concoctions free of alcohol. Click the link in our bio to read more.

Longtime and returning favorites, including Brooks & Dunn and Kenny Chesney, highlight this year's RodeoHouston lineup.

The annual event runs Feb. 28-March 19 at NRG Stadium. The 2023 lineup, announced Thursday night, features six performers taking their first spin on the rotating stage inside NRG Stadium, including Machine Gun Kelly and Walker Hayes.

Abortion restrictions have forced Texas obstetrician-gynecology residency programs to send young doctors out of the state to learn about pregnancy termination, a burdensome process educators say is another example of abortion bans undermining reproductive health care.⁠
⁠
At least one Houston-area program, the University of Texas Medical Branch, began sending residents out of state this year to a partner institution in Oregon. Two other local programs, Baylor College of Medicine and Houston Methodist, said they still are working out arrangements for their own out-of-state rotations.⁠
⁠
The changes follow revised requirements from the Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical Education, which maintains that abortion training is essential for providing comprehensive reproductive health care.⁠
⁠
Requirements updated in September say OB-GYN programs in states that ban the procedure “must provide access to this clinical experience in a different jurisdiction where it is lawful,” with exceptions for residents who choose to opt out.⁠
⁠
Experts, however, say it takes month of coordination to arrange a temporary rotation in another state, leaving some inexperienced physicians with few options. Click the link in our bio to read more.

If you’re a Netflix subscriber, there’s a good chance you’ve given your login credentials to someone outside your household. That’s a violation of the company’s terms of service, but the company has mostly turned a blind eye to it.⁠
⁠
The world's top streaming service estimates that 100 million people are mooching off its 230 million paying customers, and in April it lost subscribers for the first time in 10 years. So Netflix executives, who have been pondering putting a stop to password sharing for several years, are getting serious about it.⁠
⁠
The company told investors late last year it would crack down on violators in early 2023. But rather than hound customers who have handed out their passwords, Netflix plans to ask them to pay extra to do so.⁠
⁠
Netflix is calling the approach “paid sharing.” Those using someone else’s password are required to enter a confirmation code sent to the account owner who must provide it within 15 minutes for the sharer to begin watching.⁠
⁠
The sharing account holders pay a little more each month. The amount for U.S. customers isn't known, but it likely wouldn’t be a heavy sum, and the number of out-of-household shares would be limited.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Houston meteorologist Adam Krueger was playing Wordle last year when he came up with the idea to sneak the game's daily solution into his live weather reports.⁠
⁠
Although Krueger knew nobody would notice while watching him on CW39 Houston, he used it as a brain exercise to figure out how to naturally combine that day's word with his report.⁠
⁠
He uploaded one of his first videos to TikTok in April. At the time Krueger said he only had 30 followers.⁠
⁠
Now, he has over 189,000 followers, and his platform has snowballed from using Wordle solutions to taking suggestions from the users who comment on his videos.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Mealer tweeted she would file an election contest “after careful review and analysis of the facts available.”⁠

Much of how Houston’s skyline looks today can be traced back to Hines, a pioneering global real estate powerhouse that will celebrate its 66th anniversary in February 2023.

Since launching in Houston in the late 1950s, Hines has grown to oversee about $92 billion in properties spread across 28 countries.

While its work has left a mark across several cities, Houston was where the firm took some of its earliest risks – including adding one of the first ice skating rinks in an enclosed mall in Texas (at the Galleria) and building the tallest tower in the state.

The firm’s founder, the late Gerald D. Hines, prioritized architecturally forward-thinking designs, allowing the company to embrace unique angles, curves, distinctive glass colors and other surprising design features that would influence the industry in Houston and globally.

In downtown Houston alone, Hines has built 31 skyline-defining projects, not to mention several more across the metro. Here are a handful of the most game-changing projects in the city.

The election for Harris County judge, which ended with Democratic incumbent Lina Hidalgo fending off Republican challenger Alexandra del Moral Mealer by more than 18,000 votes, was one of the tighter and more high-profile races in the county.⁠
⁠
Late Thursday, Mealer announced her plans to file a challenge to the results of that election, alleging voter suppression – one of several candidates to do so.⁠

These moves brought swift condemnation from Harris County Attorney Christian Menefee, saying “Each of them should be deeply embarrassed, and these claims should not be taken seriously by the public.”⁠

House Speaker Dade Phelan on Thursday left the door open to legalizing sports betting and casino gambling in Texas, the latest sign that opposition may be softening among state Republican lawmakers, though the proposal still faces major hurdles in the Senate.⁠
⁠
Phelan, the Beaumont Republican who leads the Texas House, told reporters in a roundtable interview he believes voters would approve a referendum on expanded gaming options.⁠
⁠
With limited exceptions, most forms of gambling are prohibited by the Texas Constitution, which can only be amended if two-thirds of lawmakers in both chambers agree to put the matter to a statewide vote.⁠
⁠
Echoing Gov. Greg Abbott, who voiced support last fall for expanding gambling options, Phelan said he doesn’t want to “walk into every convenience store and see … slot machines.”⁠
⁠
“I want to see destination-style casinos that are high-quality and that create jobs, and that improve the lifestyles of those communities,” Phelan said. Click the link in our bio to read more.

⁠
The partners announced Thursday that the restaurant, described as flavors through the lens of “new Asian American” food, will be located in the Heights in the former Steel City Pops space.⁠

Jun is expected to open late January or early February. Click the link in our bio to read more.

⁠
Chef Reginald Scott held a soft opening for Smoke, a fast-casual BBQ restaurant specializing in smoked meats, vegetables and sides.⁠
⁠
Fire Noodz, a spicy noodle shop created by Chris Nguyen, Sonny Nguyen and Mark Tiu will serve dishes such as Thai curry ramen and fried cheesy fire balls. The opening is planned in February.⁠

Shannen and Stacey Tune, owners of Craft Burger, will open Carol Kay’s, a restaurant incorporating Southern and Caribbean cuisine, in February as well.⁠

The Houston Texans are in the market for a new head coach once again. The direction of the franchise could hinge on this decision.⁠
⁠
So, what would you do?⁠

Click the link in our bio to answer 12 questions to find out which potential coach would best fit your criteria.

Needs eggs 🥚? 

When AJ Mitchell of Cypress heard over the summer that avian flu was wiping out hens, she knew what to do: buy her own.

Now, thanks to her seven hens, including three named Cowgirl, Rodeo and Frederica, Mitchell avoids the soaring cost of eggs brought on by the flu-related deaths of millions of chickens and rising feed prices.

Instead of paying upwards of $6 a dozen at the supermarket, she and her family are among a growing number in Houston keeping chickens and enjoying fresh eggs for a fraction of that price.

What is believed to be Houston’s oldest sports bar caught fire early Friday, leading firefighters to battle a blaze that might mean a total loss for the Montrose business.⁠
⁠
Firefighters around 3:50 a.m. responded to a report of a fire in the 3400 block of Roseland Street, at Griff’s Irish Pub, and arrived to find flames coming out of the building, officials with the Houston Fire Department told On Scene reporters.⁠

Emergency responders quickly contained the blaze, but believe the building will be declared a total loss, officials said. Investigators with the arson department were working to determine the cause of the fire.⁠

Other five-figure sales included Cody Johnson (12,490), Brooks & Dunn (12,030), Chris Stapleton (11,832) and the Turnpike Troubadours (10,874). A quartet of Rodeo performers had pre-sales in 2022, including the Chainsmokers, Lauren Daigle, Parker McCollum and Cody Jinks.⁠

Houston ISD could face state takeover after the Texas Supreme Court removed a temporary injunction that paused the trial.⁠
⁠
The takeover case has been long in the making. Education Commissioner Mike Morath first made moves to take over the district’s school board in 2019 after allegations of misconduct by trustees and Phillis Wheatley High School received failing accountability grades.⁠

The following year, HISD sued and a Travis County district judge provided the district some relief by granting a temporary injunction, bringing the Texas Education Agency's plan to a halt. An appeals court upheld the injunction, but the TEA took the case to the Texas Supreme Court.⁠

Comedian Mo Amer told the Chronicle last year that with his Netflix series "Mo," he wanted to create a "sort of Palestinian origin story."⁠
⁠
Given his personal narrative — having to flee Kuwait as a child with his family — and Houston's status as an epicenter for multiple communities of immigrants, "Mo" felt very contemporary and very Houston.⁠
⁠
Having done stand-up specials for Netflix, Amer was given resources to pursue his labor of love, "Mo," a show inspired by his life. It ended in a manner that could've been final and also a doorway to a new season, Amer on a motorcycle wild-eyed and desperate to find a way back to Houston after making decisions that pulled him far from home.⁠
⁠
Whatever comes next will happen on Netflix: "Mo" was renewed by the streaming service, and will allow the writer, actor and comedian a second season to tell his story.⁠
⁠
Click the link in the bio read more.

On that summer night, like any kid his age, Paul Vasquez wanted to play video games before bed.⁠
⁠
The 8-year-old boy was grabbing a charging cord for his PlayStation when gunfire from a drive-by shooter erupted through the front of his family's narrow mobile home in northeast Harris County, puncturing holes in the wall and striking him once in the torso.⁠
⁠
Vasquez did not make it. His death bisected a year in which dozens of Harris County families buried kids killed in shootings.⁠
⁠
Sixty children and adolescents under 18 died from gunshot wounds in 2022 in the nation’s third most populous county, according to the Harris County Institute of Forensic Sciences, making last year the deadliest in at least five years for the Houston area’s youngest residents.⁠
⁠
That number includes 47 homicides, 12 suicides and one accident. Click the link in our bio to read more.

⁠
This year's lineup, which runs from Feb. 28- March 19 at NRG Stadium, features longtime and returning performers, six new rodeo performers and six noncountry acts.⁠
⁠
Many people on social media were looking forward to the plethora of country acts, with longtime favorites Cody Johnson, Brooks & Dunn and Luke Bryan. Local favorite Parker McCollum of Conroe also continues to win over more fans each year.⁠
⁠
But others criticized RodeoHouston's Go Tejano Day for not featuring a Tejano artist, and others are less than ecstatic about seeing Machine Gun Kelly as one of the noncountry performers, compared to big-name performers of the past like Mary J. Blige, Ariana Grande, and Pitbull.⁠

As the Houston region continues to develop over the next few years, wildlife removal experts say that interactions between coyotes and humans will steadily increase until their encounters are a more common occurrence.⁠
⁠
Coyote sightings in Houston used to be rare and could be the subject of viral moments, like the video last year of a coyote scaling a fence and roof in a Richmond backyard.⁠
⁠
Mark Browning from Houston's Elite Wildlife Services said that years ago coyotes would normally only be seen on the outskirts of undeveloped properties. But as more areas get developed, there has been an uptick in calls for coyote removal services in more urbanized zones.⁠
⁠
For instance, a few weeks ago Browning said that his company received a call about a coyote on the top floor of a downtown parking garage, calling the ordeal a "spectacle," with people afraid the coyote was going to bite someone.⁠
⁠
There were also recent reports of coyote sightings near Memorial Park in Houston. Click the link in our bio to read more.

The Texas prison system has a new goal: Serving slightly more edible food.⁠
⁠
As part of a long-term strategic plan, the corrections agency aims to do away with the worst of prison fare — the meager and sometimes moldy brown-bag meals served during lockdowns, which occur regularly and can last for weeks.⁠
⁠
Though lockdown meals have generated complaints for years, the public didn’t get a look at how awful they really were until 2020, when The Marshall Project and Hearst Newspapers published images of them captured with contraband phones.⁠
⁠
Afterward, the food improved in some prisons — but only for a short time, prisoners reported.⁠
⁠
Now, though, the agency is making plans for more permanent improvements by starting a new culinary training program in hopes of doing away with cold meals altogether.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

⁠
Senate Bill 465 would make it illegal to possess a catalytic converter removed from a vehicle unless on a list of businesses allowed to possess it, such as an automotive shop, said state Sen. Paul Bettencourt, R-Houston, who filed the bill.⁠
⁠
If anyone on the approved list knows the converter was acquired illegally, however, they are not protected under the proposed legislation.⁠
⁠
Senate Bill 432, filed by Sen. Mayes Middleton, R-Galveston, would make it a felony to steal a catalytic converter.⁠
⁠
The Houston region saw a spike in catalytic converter thefts, including one case that led to murder charges, Police Chief Troy Finner said in May.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Under the proposal, scheduled for a vote by the Metropolitan Transit Authority board next week, Metro would take over bike sharing in the area and integrate it into its own plans for encouraging bus and train riders to access stops.⁠

The proposed partnership is welcomed by Houston Bike Share, the nonprofit created in 2012 to develop the bike sharing system in Houston, using BCycle’s kiosk-based bikes.⁠

Many would-be homebuyers are facing the same question as they face inflation and higher mortgage rates. With Houston-area rents and home prices up, does it make more sense to buy a house or to rent one?⁠

Answers will vary based on personal finances, lifestyles and goals. Is your house a place to live or a wealth-building tool? Is it better to build wealth by investing in real estate or the stock market? Or is saving as much money as possible in the short term the biggest concern?⁠

On a cool January evening at the Sharpstown Park Golf Course, Father Jeff Johnson of @strakejesuit patrolled the carpeted floors of a burger restaurant - past the fryer, past the old-timey photos and past the Elvis statue - to uplift the space in the eyes of God.

“Bless all who will work here at Prince’s, so that in the work of hospitality, they will emulate Christ who welcomed all to his everlasting banquet,” Johnson said.

To bless Prince’s Hamburgers may be an exercise in repetition. For the past 94 years, the restaurant has survived (and sometimes thrived) amid changing owners, changing tastes and global economic shakeups.

A little divine assistance might be suspected for Prince’s longevity but for the grounded skeptics, there is another powerful force at work here: nostalgia.

The women worked at different businesses in an east Houston office building where the janitor, Lucio Diaz, was tasked with cleaning at night. Miami-based developer Resia is progressing on the community, called Resia Ten Oaks, after securing a $96.5 million loan for the project, at 18036 Park Row, about 22 miles west of downtown Houston and 9 miles east of Katy.⁠
⁠

When James Coney Island was founded in 1923, there was no McDonald's, no Whataburger, no Burger King.⁠
⁠
There was only a hot dog stand in downtown Houston run by two brothers, both Greek immigrants. Now, that stand is gone, along with all of the chain's locations within the Inner Loop.⁠
⁠
Over the past four years, the company, recently rebranded as JCI Grill, has cut its number of locations in half as the pandemic, remote work and demographic shifts have made the Houston area a much different landscape for a fast food restaurant in 2023 than it was 100 years ago.⁠
⁠
But while drivers may take the large "closed" signs on Westheimer Road and South Shepherd Drive as signs of weakness, JCI President Darrin Straughan says it's all part of a plan.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Harris County is no stranger to floods. More than a third of the county’s land falls within a FEMA-designated flood plain – a figure expected to increase substantially when FEMA releases updated maps for Harris County later this year.

Despite the fact that researchers expect sea levels to rise faster in the Western Gulf than any other area in the U.S., development in the county’s flood-prone areas has been happening for decades. This doesn’t just put those living in and around flood plains at risk, but it can actually make flooding worse.

What constitutes flood plain development is a subject of debate. Harris County Engineer Milton Rahman insists the county doesn't allow people to build in the flood plain. If a developer can meet certain regulations, such as raising construction 2 feet above the 500-year flood level, the county no longer considers that area to be in the flood plain.

Critics argue this approach obscures true flood risks, especially as significant flooding routinely occurs outside FEMA’s flood plains. In fact, many have questioned the accuracy of the FEMA maps, which are used to determine development policy and insurance costs.

As the population of Harris County balloons, urban sprawl continues to encroach on flood plains.

Click the link in our bio to read more.

⁠
The variety of reasons probably outnumber the unique vocabulary.⁠
⁠
“It is a big problem,” said Mike Manser, a senior research scientist at the Texas A&M Transportation Institute. “It is a continual problem, and it is complex because there is not one area to focus on.”⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Alicia Rowe, an Austin therapist, first came across news of her death in a British tabloid.⁠
⁠
The Daily Mail UK had run a story online about how her parents, Kathleen and George Rowe, had been sued for feeding the neighborhood ducks after feuding with their homeowners’ association in Cypress.⁠
⁠
The article offered zero ambiguity about her demise: “Texas couple who began feeding neighborhood ducks to cope with loss of only daughter are sued for (up to) $250,000 by HOA for causing a nuisance and are forced to sell home to cover costs,” read the article’s headline.⁠
⁠
Alicia, who is in her 30s, was the Rowes’ only child. She stared at the article in shock. Then she wondered how she had died. She had her suspicions.⁠
⁠
When she texted friends about the surreal development, they quickly found that versions of the story, which first ran in the Houston Chronicle in July, were everywhere: Alicia had also died in the Washington Post, in Business Insider India and in the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.⁠
⁠

Food critic Alison Cook decided this was the year — and the Carnival season — when she would make her peace with the king cake.

She was determined to find Houston-area king cake versions that suited her. And she did.

This edible totem of the weeks from Epiphany to Lent, all leading to the pagan revelry of Mardi Gras, is much loved by Houstonians. The king cake’s allure, its braids of sweet yeast dough etched out in cheerfully lurid Carnival colors of purple, green and gold, has extended beyond our boisterous cadre of Louisiana expats to encompass the entire city.

Everybody gets into the act. Jewish bakeries, old-school German bakeries, brunch hot spots trading in Mardi Gras-hued king cake French toast. King Cake milk punch? King Cake babka? We got ‘em.

Smash burger fans who are waiting patiently for Trill Burgers to open its first permanent location can get their fix at the 2023 Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo.⁠
⁠
For the second year, Bun B’s Trill Burgers will be among the food vendors at RodeoHouston, Feb. 28 to March 19, taking up home at Rodeo Plaza near the Champion Wine Garden and Astrodome.⁠
⁠
Trill Burgers made its rodeo debut last year, serving more than 12,000 burgers during the 21-day run. Bun B’s Southern Takeover at NRG Stadium will be on March 3.⁠

⁠
Named for one of the brightest stars in the sky in the Orion constellation, the funky bar with a menu of “ironclad” pizzas baked in cast iron pans, is set to take up home in the site of Bamboo restaurant.⁠
⁠
“We can’t believe how lucky we are to have found this space in one of our favorite neighborhoods in Houston — and we’re gonna get real weird with it,” owner Chris Cusack stated. “We’re super excited to share even more pizza and cocktails with Montrose!”⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

The Texas entrepreneur working to bring back the woolly mammoth has added a new species to his revival list: the dodo.⁠
⁠
Recreating this flightless bird, a symbol of human-caused extinction, is a chance for redemption. It might also motivate humans to remove invasive species from Mauritius, the bird's native habitat, said Ben Lamm, CEO and co-founder of Colossal Biosciences.⁠
⁠
"Humanity can undo the sins of the past with these advancing genetic rescue technologies," Lamm said. "There is always a benefit for carefully planned rewilding of a species back into its native environment."⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Domonique Champion could not stay silent about the events of Nov. 4, not once University of Houston theater instructors presented seniors with the green construction vests.⁠
⁠
Suddenly everyone in the department was talking about his trauma. While he and a classmate were outside practicing a scene calling for “heightened, choreographed” violence from "Lie of the Mind," a play by Sam Shepard, a white UH police officer arrived with his gun drawn in response to a bystander's report of an assault, Champion said.⁠
⁠
His school had handed out the vests – to some, months later – as a way to show authorities that its students were not threats.⁠
⁠
Champion is all too aware what other students are now realizing. A green vest would not have protected him, an unarmed Black man, from a bullet.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

These 10 businesses are some of the area’s best-loved Black-owned eateries, offering everything from healthy vegan meals to decadent desserts.

Mutt Neuman, 77, lives for the rodeo. He’s a bull riding champion and a veteran bullfighter and rodeo clown.

He’s a Dayton native, born back before the town swelled to its population of 9,000; back when you could scramble onto a sheep just about anywhere if you wanted to grow up to ride bulls.

That’s the thing with boys these days. With what Mutt calls the city life encroaching on Dayton, there’s kids who don’t have the opportunity to be hands-on with livestock. The number of self-made cowboys — the ones who taught themselves without going to a school — are on the decline.

So Mutt teaches them, but more than 35 miles away from the crowds and the noise of the Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo. On Thursdays, boys gather at the Bar-N-Bar Arena, which he built in Dayton around 1966 out of metal piping that a buddy in the oilfield business helped him acquire.

Yes, Houston has rattlesnakes. 🐍⁠
⁠
Will one show up on your driveway? Probably not.⁠
⁠
“Rattlesnakes are much less common in the city of Houston,” said Berri Moffett, a conservation specialist with Houston Audubon. “They’re just a little more nervous. They’re more shy.”⁠
⁠
Make no mistake. Houston has rattlesnakes. The most common is the Western Diamondback. It’s the biggest and most widespread rattler around here, averaging four feet long. They eat small mammals and often forage around farm buildings.⁠
⁠
But rattlesnakes are uncommon in urban areas because they need better habitats, said Greg Pandelis, curator of the Amphibian and Reptile Diversity Research Center at The University of Texas at Arlington.⁠
⁠
They need more space. The smaller yards that often come with urban areas generally aren't big enough for rattlers to hide, eat and mate, he said.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Prominent GOP activist and donor Steven Hotze was kicked out of a Texas Senate committee hearing Thursday night after he refused to stop labeling transgender people and those who support them as pedophiles.⁠
⁠
Four bills targeting transgender youth and adults were on the state affairs committee's agenda Thursday, including one that would ban gender-affirming care for minors. Most major medical associations classify transition care as medically necessary.⁠
⁠
Testimony was split, with some witnesses in support saying the bills would protect children who are too young to know their gender identity and other witnesses saying the bills constitute government overreach that will endanger the mental and physical wellbeing of already-at-risk transgender youth.⁠
⁠
Hotze — a Houston physician who is openly anti-LGBTQ and is facing felony criminal charges in Harris County related to a privately funded voter-fraud inquiry — had been testifying in favor of the bills when state Sen. José Menéndez addressed his language, asking him to refrain from using the "criminal" term pedophile when referring to transgender people and their supporters.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Overindulging on green beer today? 🍀 An ounce of prevention goes a long way.

Here are six things to keep in mind before you’ve had one too many — or after. Click the link in our bio to read more.

Inflation has nudged many shoppers, across the nation, to opt for private label products at their local grocers.

But Texans who shop at H-E-B didn't need that push, the Houston Chronicle discovered when we turned to Twitter for a straw poll, asking readers who buy the store's private label products if they do so for value, or if they prefer the products — and if so, which products in particular.

"Hatch Salsa! Cheese Crunchies! Cooking oil! BBQ Sauce! Milk! American cheese! Bacon! Juice boxes! Flour! Salt!" said one reader.

"Everything is awesome," agreed another.

Still, we tried to narrow it down. Here are five H-E-B products you have to try, as recommended by our readers. Click the link in our bio to read more.

The eggs laid by radiated tortoise Mrs. Pickles roughly five months ago have hatched at the Houston Zoo, revealing three tiny offspring: Dill, Gherkin and Jalapeno. 🐢⁠
⁠
The father, Mr. Pickles, is the the oldest animal at the Houston Zoo and is the most genetically valuable radiated tortoise in the Association of Zoos and Aquariums’ Species Survival Plan.⁠
⁠
Mr. Pickles, 90, has been at the zoo for 36 years, while Mrs. Pickles arrived in 1996. They have been fan favorites of zoo goers for years. The pair have only reproduced one other time in 1997 with one hatchling.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

In 2019, Christine Ha opened her first restaurant, the Blind Goat.⁠
⁠
The Blind Goat was meant to be a platform for Ha’s personal takes on classic Vietnamese dishes. Ambitions and expectations were high.⁠
⁠
But operating inside the Bravery Chef Hall, a downtown food court, for the first-time restaurant owner presented challenges — from limited kitchen space to an office worker-driven crowd that shriveled up during the pandemic. Ha’s second restaurant Xin Chào opened a year later off the Washington Corridor.⁠
⁠
Fast forward nearly a decade since Ha won the third season of “MasterChef,” the Blind Goat has reopened in a new location. A brick-and-mortar space opened at the end of February at Spring Branch Village development.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio for 5 must-try dishes.

The price of eggs may be easing slightly, but the staple is still too expensive for Dollar Tree.⁠
⁠
The company is no longer selling eggs in its stores as of this week, and does not expect to resume selling eggs until this fall at the earliest, Reuters reported.⁠
⁠
The move is a response to wholesale egg prices, which soared in 2022, pushing the retail price of a dozen Grade A eggs to $4.82 in January 2023, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics. That's a record high, and up from $1.93 in January 2022.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

As Texans continue paying off the costs of the deadly 2021 winter storm, state lawmakers are considering a Republican-backed proposal that would allow for more frequent rate hikes and prevent cities from challenging the increases.⁠
⁠
Supporters of Senate Bill 1015 say it would help bolster the power grid, making it easier for utilities to recover the costs of building poles and wires to transmit electricity across growing cities.⁠
⁠
SB 1015 would let utilities seek two distribution rate hikes a year, including when they have a rate case pending. And it would make the PUC, not cities, responsible for reviewing and challenging the hikes.⁠
⁠
Critics say the bill would cost ratepayers millions. It would amount to "utility self-regulation," with “the potential of multiple, sizable increases to ratepayers over a very short period,” argued Tina Paez, director of Houston's Administration and Regulatory Affairs Department.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Allergies in Houston are no joke. The city was ranked as the No. 12 most challenging city for allergies by the Asthma and Allergy Foundation of America.⁠
⁠
The foundation's 2023 report pushed Houston up 22 spots from last year's No. 34 ranking for worst allergies. Still, it could be worse. Dallas, at No. 2, was the only Texas city to break into the top 10.⁠
⁠
Wichita, Kansas was ranked No. 1. Click the link in our bio to read more.

The Houston Cougars battle back from a 10-point halftime deficit to advance to their fourth straight #sweet16 in the #ncaatournament with an 81-64 win over Auburn. Marcus Sasser and Tremon Mark combined for 48 points to lead the Cougars. #marchmadness #uhcougars #ncaa 📷 @bcoomer713 #houstonchronicle @uhcougarmbk

Michael Galloway leads workouts with the unrelenting optimism of any good personal trainer. "It's not how you start, it's how you finish!" the 33-year-old yells as he leads exhausted clients through series of squats, burpees and deadlifts.⁠
⁠
Coming from anyone else, the expression may sound like a cliche meant to carry you to the end of a workout. Though, to know Galloway's journey — from accidentally killing his friend to starting his own business, X-Cons Fitness, and blowing up on TikTok — is to know how personal the mantra is.⁠
⁠
"It took everything in my past to make the me person I am today. I'm not ashamed of my past. I take ownership of all the mistakes that I've made," Galloway said.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Whether they’re shooting it, sipping it or mixing it in a margarita, one thing’s for certain: Texans love their tequila.⁠
⁠
On April 13, tequila lovers can learn more about their favorite spirit and taste some of the finest tequila on the market at the Nach-Yo Ordinary Tequila Tasting hosted at The Ark by Norris event center.⁠
⁠
The featured tequilas will be craft and relatively obscure spirits, said Constance McDerby, media relations for the Nach-Yo Ordinary Tequila Tasting, making it the perfect opportunity for tequila lovers to branch out and try new brands.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

It’s crawfish season — and in Houston, that means it’s also crawfish ice cream season. No, really.⁠
⁠
“Well, we’re in Texas!” said Nickey Ngo, owner of Red Circle Ice Cream, on Saturday, as a steady stream of customers visited the shop’s original location in southwest Houston.⁠
⁠
Several years ago, she explained, she was driving to dinner with her husband when inspiration struck. She thought that year’s crawfish ice cream experiment would be a one-time thing, but because of customer demand, Red Circle decided to bring back the flavor annually during spring break.⁠
⁠
The crawfish ice cream will be available through the end of the week, Ngo says — unless it sells out first. Click the link in our bio to read more.

Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, a mainstay in Houston politics for more than three decades, is running for mayor.⁠
⁠
In broadcast remarks at City Cathedral Church, the congresswoman said on stage that she intends to run in the November election to succeed Mayor Sylvester Turner, who is term-limited.⁠
⁠
"Sheila Jackson Lee wants to come home to be your mayor, for the city of Houston," Jackson Lee said in the video, also shared on social media.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio for more info.

The Texas Observer is on the verge of shutting down after nearly 70 years of publishing as a often-lone voice of progressive dissent in a largely conservative political landscape — although some on the magazine's staff say they are fighting for a reprieve.⁠
⁠
The news, first reported Sunday by the Texas Tribune, is due to a decision of the nonprofit Texas Democracy Foundation, which owns the magazine. The foundation's board voted last week to close the Observer and lay off its 17 staff members, including 13 journalists.⁠
⁠
But on Monday Gabriel Arana, the Observer's editor in chief, said that staff will ask for a reprieve.⁠
⁠
"The Texas Observer is not like a Walmart that can just be shut down," he said in a tweet. "We’ve asked the board members who voted to quit to resign and allow those of us who want to see the legacy continue do the work."⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

The Final Four's fourth trip to Houston seemed perfectly suited for a dream scenario. The University of Houston, conveniently located just five miles from NRG Stadium, was set up as a No. 1 seed to play for a title at home.⁠
⁠
Plan B was for Texas, a two-seed located just 160 miles west, to make it in the Cougars place and bathe the home of the Houston Texans in burnt orange.⁠
⁠
Instead, Miami pulled off a Texas Two-Step by eliminating both, and now the Final Four field consists of schools about as far-flung as possible with underdog Florida Atlantic University, located 1,150 miles away in Boca Raton, Fla., checking in as the closest locale.⁠
⁠
The long distances combined with UConn being the closest thing to a basketball blue blood coming to Houston is a nightmare scenario for anyone trying to make money off their Final Four tickets.⁠
⁠
Make no mistake: The Final Four is a sellout and NRG Stadium will be full, but prices on the resell market dipped when Houston was eliminated Friday night and took a nosedive when Texas got the axe Sunday.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

When the weather is nice, the scene on the sidewalk patio in front of Hẻm, a new Vietnamese restaurant and bar in Asiatown, is reminiscent of the street-side cafes in Vietnam.

In the morning, older generation Vietnamese gather for coffee and conversation. By lunch, the crowd becomes more diverse as customers feast on a lunch menu that includes sizzling steak and egg and combination broken rice plates. Come dinnertime, Hẻm’s full menu comes into play, with dishes such as fried frog legs, shaken beef, and razor clams grilled with oil and scallions.

Occupying a prominent location in the center of Ai Hoa Plaza on Bellaire since its soft opening in late January, Hẻm, which means “alley” in Vietnamese, has quickly become a must-visit restaurant in Asiatown. Weekends are packed, as are most evenings, when there is often a wait at this trendy spot.

Click the link in our bio to read more.

Thinking about switching to an electric car? More charging stations are popping up around Houston and beyond, and for daily commutes, changing to an electric vehicle takes some fairly small adjustments.⁠
⁠
While local trips around town can help avoid “range anxiety,” those thinking of buying an EV often worry about going on a road trip and being unable to find a charging station.⁠
⁠
The Chronicle put together an electric vehicle road trip planner to help those thinking about making the switch to an EV figure out what models meet their budget and road trip needs.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to explore.

Arrijana Hill was 16 years old and pregnant with twins when her boyfriend stabbed her and strangled her to death in her family's suburban home.⁠
⁠
As the Hill family nears the ninth anniversary of her murder, her mother, Opal Hill, is frustrated that a recent surge of domestic violence killings in Harris County is the latest reminder that her daughter's death was merely an early data point of a grim trend.⁠
⁠
Domestic violence-related homicides doubled in Harris County between 2019 and 2022, a University of Houston study reports. Experts say the stark numbers aren’t an outlier — more and more women across Texas are falling victim to domestic violence each year.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Anglers, hikers and nature lovers are soaking in Fairfield Lake State Park’s brief reopening before they’ll have to pack up their poles for good.⁠
⁠
The 1,460-acre state park, which the state leased from Vistra Corp for nearly 50 years, closed Feb. 28. Two weeks earlier, the private company announced its plan to end the park lease and sell the land to Todd Interests, which plans to develop the land into a gated community with million-dollar homes and a private golf course.⁠
⁠
Fairfield Lake State Park abruptly reopened March 14. In a release, the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department said it would allow free entry to day-use visitors only for as long as they’d be allowed to. The state has until June to vacate the park.⁠
⁠
Spring breakers, hikers and anglers quickly flocked back to Fairfield Lake. Click the link in our bio to read more.

Many parents of special education students in Houston ISD who feel the school system has failed their children are deeply conflicted over news of the state takeover.⁠
⁠
Some who say their children have been denied federally protected rights to an education believe a takeover is long overdue. Others agree accountability is needed, but question whether the Texas Education Agency has the capacity or track record necessary to execute change for the better.⁠
⁠
Both entities have received intense criticism of their delivery of special education services for decades.⁠
⁠
The school system's special education department’s “significant systemic compliance problems” were cited among the reasons in TEA Commissioner Mike Morath’s notice that a state-appointed board of managers will soon lead the district.⁠
⁠
However, some advocates say they anticipate little change to the beleaguered department given that state-appointed conservators have overseen it for years.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

As the spring season kicks off, Houston residents have another nuisance to keep an eye on besides allergies and rainy weather: tent caterpillar mating season. 🐛⁠
⁠
Houstonians may see big groups of fuzzy, small caterpillars on trees, patios, sides of houses and other structures as the small insects congregate for their mating season.⁠
⁠
Tent caterpillars form webs from their fecal matter, creating the tent-like structure that gives them their name. Instead of turning into a butterfly like other species of caterpillar, tent caterpillars grow into white moths.⁠
⁠
While they are not harmful on their own, masses of tent caterpillars have caused power outages in Houston in the past, covering pieces of electrical equipment.⁠
⁠
They can be removed with glue traps and water hoses, but pest control can control larger clusters of the insect.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to learn more.

Watch out for Airbnb scams if you're in Houston for the Final Four of the NCAA Tournament.⁠
⁠
Airbnb is warning fans to watch out for third-party scams that use its and other companies' likeness while offering what can be considered a bargain deal. In some cases, the scammer will then ask the buyer to wire them money directly to process the reservation, Airbnb said.⁠
⁠
There are also possible fake listings on Airbnb. The company recommends that guests booking through the platform examine ratings and reviews to ensure their stay is legitimate.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.⁠

Faced with ongoing school bus driver shortages, school districts across the Houston area are offering better pay and job perks, and some have been forced to call on staff from other departments to cover vacant routes.⁠
⁠
Pay boosts and frequent job fairs have become common practice for school districts grappling with persistent driver shortages. Many have been struggling to fill vacancies for years.⁠
⁠
“Bus drivers have been a difficult-to-fill position perennially. That was the case pre-pandemic, and it was the case during the pandemic and continues to be true,” said Amy Campbell, Texas Association of School Boards human resources director.⁠
⁠
The problem was worsened by the pandemic as school districts saw budget cuts and drivers leaving the workforce. Click the link in our bio to read more.

The Final Four has come and gone, but an accusation against one of Houston's popular restaurants is leaving a lingering sting.⁠
⁠
UConn shooting guard Jordan Hawkins came down with what he said was food poisoning over the weekend before the semifinals against Miami. Chronicle sports writer Matt Young reported he ate steak, macaroni and cheese, mashed potatoes and calamari.⁠
⁠
Hawkins later spoke to Stadium analyst Jeff Goodman and said his intense stomach pains might have been the calamari from Mastro's Steakhouse.⁠
⁠
Jim Gossen, president of the Gulf Seafood Foundation, spoke in defense of Mastro's (and all seafood) by implying Hawkins had probably drank too much alcohol.⁠
⁠
“They always blame the oyster, they never blame the Crown Royal,” Gossen said. Click the link in our bio to read more.

One of the best free activities to do in Houston is hunt down murals. 

Choose an area to explore and find all the nearby murals with the Houston Mural Map. According to the site, there are about 750 murals in the city. You'll find them big and bigger across buildings with faces, space and nature. 

Click the link in our bio to explore more.

As Texas legislators continue debating the possible expansion of the state's medical marijuana program, many Texans already have prescriptions to use the drug legally, under certain conditions.⁠
⁠
Eligible Texans suffering from specific ailments have been able to legally use medical marijuana since 2015 when the Compassionate Use Act was passed. The compassionate use program grants qualified physicians the ability to prescribe "low THC" cannabis to patients with certain medical conditions.⁠
⁠
A House committee in late March unanimously approved the bill presented by state Rep. Stephanie Klick, which would boost the maximum allowable THC level in medical marijuana from 1 percent to 5 percent and allow the Department of State Health Services to add additional qualifying conditions.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio for a list of the conditions that qualify a Texas resident to be prescribed medical marijuana.

Marriott Marquis Houston’s Texas-shaped swimming pool earned the downtown facility the top spot on a list of the nation’s 14 best hotels with a lazy river selected by Travel + Leisure.⁠
⁠
With summer just around the corner, Marriott Marquis Houston entices visitors with its 530-foot rooftop lazy river in the shape of its home state. Guests can also take in downtown Houston’s impressive view from the hotel’s infinity pool, adult-only hot tub or cocktail bar – all located on the rooftop deck.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Driverless commercial trucks will begin traveling between Dallas and Houston by the end of 2024.⁠
⁠
Self-driving tech firm Aurora Innovation announced it has entered the final phase of refinement for its autonomous technology ahead of the official launch of the driverless trucks. Aurora Innovation is the latest company to expand its presence in the region with self-driving trucks.⁠
⁠
Its patented software has been updated over the last 18 months dozens of times it says, increasing autonomous performance, safety and reliability in pilot hauls for companies like FedEx, Werner, Schneider and Uber Freight.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

Texas' updated version of the STAAR test launches across the state in April, and it's crunch time for students and teachers to prepare.⁠
Testing for the State of Texas Assessment of Academic Readiness will take place from April 18 through May 12.⁠
⁠
The 2023 STARR test has been updated in several key areas, including the elimination of the Scantron test sheet and, for the first time, the transition to an exclusively online testing process.⁠
⁠
Under House Bill 3906, passed by the 86th Texas Legislature in 2019, the test will have fewer multiple-choice options, with just 75 percent of students’ score based on multiple-choice answers, and students can receive partial credit for some answers.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio for a detailed schedule.

⁠
But superfans should be ready to shovel out nearly $1,000 per person for even the worst seats as supply and demand mean the market for resale runs rampant.⁠

Taylor Swift’s world tour started in Arizona last month and fans have since flooded social media with pictures and videos from her shows. The last time Swift toured was in 2018.⁠

It’s no secret Houston fans love to cheer on the Astros with a cold drink in hand, but you might be surprised at how much.⁠
⁠
Minute Maid Park sold the second-highest amount of alcohol of any professional sports venue in Texas last year, finishing behind only the Dallas Cowboys’ AT&T Stadium, according to data from the Texas Comptroller of Public Accounts.⁠
⁠
In 2022 alone, fans spent more than $28 million on alcohol at Minute Maid Park’s bars while cheering on the team to another World Series title. That's only 22% less than customers spent at AT&T Stadium — an impressive feat considering the capacity at Minute Maid Park is less than half that of the Arlington football venue.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

On a weekday afternoon, if the sidewalks in downtown Houston look especially bare, it could be because all the pedestrians can be found beneath them.⁠
⁠
The tunnel system is a woven maze of pathways and halls leading to food courts and shopping strips for Houstonians to eat, shop and socialize during their lunch breaks.⁠
⁠
It has become an integral network of underground businesses that employees and citizens access through elevators, skybridges and stairs.⁠
⁠
Click the link in the bio to read more.

An artificial Martian environment is tucked deep within NASA’s Johnson Space Center in Houston. And in two months, it will shelter four people for a 378-day mission that simulates living on Mars.

In Houston and across the country, Latino LGBTQ leaders are split on the gender-neutral terms Latinx and Latine.⁠
⁠
The terms have grown more popular in recent years as a way to be more inclusive to women and the LGBTQ community by replacing the traditionally masculine -o suffix in Latino with -x or -e.⁠
⁠
What term resonates most with you and why? Comment below ⬇️

Dr. Cesar A. Soutullo frequently finds himself writing prescriptions for Adderall two, three or even four times before his patients can find ADHD medication in stock at a pharmacy.⁠
⁠
It’s been six months since the U.S. Food and Drug Administration first announced a nationwide shortage of amphetamine mixed salts, commonly known by the brand name Adderall.⁠
⁠
Soutullo, a professor of psychiatry at UTHealth Houston and the director of the ADHD Outpatient Program at McGovern Medical School, said some patients are running out of medication before they can find a refill.⁠
⁠
He said he’s spoken to parents with children who’ve had trouble paying attention in school or been overly active without their medication.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

A teacher for the Houston Independent School District was arrested earlier this month near the Texas-Mexico border when authorities said they found four migrants in the teacher's car.⁠
⁠
Police say the man who was arrested, Brandan Gracia, was driving to Houston April 2 when he was stopped by officials on Las Moras Road because of an unspecified traffic violation.⁠
⁠
In a Facebook post, officials with the Kinney County Sheriff's Office said deputies from Galveston County found four migrants in the car with Gracia.⁠
⁠
The sheriff's office also said Gracia had been in possession of an ID badge from Patrick Henry Middle School when he was stopped.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

While most of the world longs for wealth, Texas has been blessed with its own pot of gold. And it’s filled with gooey yellow cheese.⁠
⁠
Chile con queso, that essential Tex-Mex dip with bits of tomato, chopped green chile and onion, is practically a Texas birthright of the culinary kind.⁠
⁠
Almost every Tex-Mex restaurant worth its salt has its own spin on chile con queso (or, more infrequently, its queso flameado cousin).⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio for a list of Houston’s favorite quesos.

Conservative Republicans are slamming their colleague, state Rep. Bryan Slaton, after reports emerged this week of an ethics complaint filed against him alleging he had an inappropriate relationship with an intern.⁠
⁠
So far, two GOP lawmakers have called for Slaton to resign and a third has proposed amending a bill creating the criminal offense of child grooming to specifically target his alleged activity.⁠
⁠
All of the members rebuking Slaton are, like him, among the most conservative of the Texas Legislature and typically agree with him politically.⁠
⁠
Slaton, a former Baptist minister and youth pastor from North Texas, has not responded to the allegations, aside from his attorney putting out a statement calling them "outrageous" and "false."⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read more.

You don't need a DeLorean to get back to the 1980s with this Houston home that recently went on the market.⁠
⁠
In the Mid-West neighborhood at 2110 Amberly Court, a retro architectural gem sits boasting a half-moon court yard, thick glass-block walls and a standout floating staircase.⁠
⁠
Really making the home special is that is was the last project by local architect Ralph A. Anderson, Jr., whose previous work included the Astrodome and Houston Post building. The 3,294-square-foot custom home was built in 1988 and has only had two owners.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to learn more.

Houston formally abandoned an ordinance Wednesday that banned buskers throughout most of the city, four months after it was struck down by a federal judge.⁠
⁠
For decades, Houston made busking — musicians and other artists performing on streets for cash tips — illegal throughout most of the city. In 1991, it confined the performances only to the Theater District and required interested performers to obtain a permit.⁠
⁠
Federal Judge Alfred H. Bennett declared that legal framework unconstitutional in December, ruling the ordinances violated the First Amendment.⁠
⁠
Instead of appealing the ruling, City Council voted unanimously Wednesday to drop those portions of its code. Click the link in our bio to read more.

The Houston Parks and Recreation Department is looking to fill positions for the 2023 swimming season after experiencing a shortage of lifeguards last summer.⁠
⁠
According to Houston Public Media, the city has 950 recruits lined up, which is triple from the 345 recruits last year.⁠
⁠
Although the city has not officially hired any lifeguards yet, they need to hire at least 187 in order to open up all of its 37 aquatic facilities operated by the Parks and Recreation Department.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to learn more.

A landlord accused of allowing residents to live in unsafe conditions at an east Houston apartment complex has lost four Houston apartment communities with more than 3,200 units in a foreclosure, underscoring how even owners of large apartment portfolios can fall victim to rising interest rates and inflation.⁠
⁠

SpaceX still considered the launch a success as it didn't blow up the launch pad, and the company will use the data on future launches from Boca Chica.
